Other declarations in the same form — “Health care is quintessentially axiomatic,” “Health care is candy-apple gray,” “Health care is a spastically cloistered bottle of courageous smoke,” etc.
AdvertisementSenator Sanders points to the Scandinavian model as an example of what it means to have health care as a right.
AdvertisementAnother thing the Scandinavian countries have in common: Their politicians may talk about health care as a right sometimes, too, but in none of those countries is health care free.
AdvertisementThere isn’t a single “Scandinavian” model of health care, but there are some features common in the set.
One of them is that consumers pay out of pocket for health care, starting with copays but also extending to many specialist services, prescription drugs, dental care, and the like.